WEBVTT

00:04.964 --> 00:06.882
[Wild Bill]
Previously on Heels...

00:07.049 --> 00:08.926
[Tom] Man,
we are losing money.

00:09.093 --> 00:10.636
We are losing so
much fuckin' money.

00:10.803 --> 00:12.304
I'm such a fuckin' failure.

00:12.471 --> 00:13.973
What's going on here, Willie?

00:14.098 --> 00:15.433
Tom and I made
an agreement years ago

00:15.599 --> 00:17.017
that we would do
whatever we need to do

00:17.184 --> 00:18.894
to keep this place alive,

00:19.019 --> 00:20.896
and you don't need to worry
about what those things are.

00:21.063 --> 00:22.773
-Are they legal?
-Some are.

00:22.940 --> 00:25.276
[Staci] Well, whatever
those other ones are,

00:25.443 --> 00:27.027
we're not doing 'em anymore.

00:28.112 --> 00:29.488
[commentator] For those of
you wondering what was that,

00:29.655 --> 00:31.699
that was The Condamned.

00:31.866 --> 00:34.160
-[Jack] Ace Spade is back.
-[Gully] Dystopia was

00:34.326 --> 00:36.203
supposed to end the night up
with a ring invasion.

00:36.370 --> 00:39.123
Instead, we end the night down
in front of a thousand people.

00:39.248 --> 00:41.542
I am not used to having to
run everything by a partner.

00:41.709 --> 00:42.752
Get used to it!

00:42.918 --> 00:44.462
Or the lawsuit is back on!

00:44.628 --> 00:46.964
So I have some thoughts
on how this should go.

00:47.131 --> 00:49.759
Why should I let you book
what happens in my ring

00:49.925 --> 00:51.927
and trust that you're actually
gonna go through with it?

00:52.094 --> 00:54.305
Well, first off, you get
to punch me in the face.

00:54.472 --> 00:56.348
-Yay, Dad.
-Yeah. Yay, me.

00:56.515 --> 00:57.808
[Brooks] Last year,
total revenue

00:57.975 --> 01:01.353
from professional wrestling
was 1.095 billion.

01:01.520 --> 01:03.397
I guess I could grow to love
professional wrestling.

01:03.564 --> 01:04.440
[Gully]
Brooks Rizzo just texted.

01:04.607 --> 01:05.816
He's gonna be
a little bit late.

01:05.983 --> 01:06.984
We're not gonna start
the show without him.

01:07.151 --> 01:08.194
So meet him out there
for will-call,

01:08.319 --> 01:09.570
sit next to him
during the show.

01:09.737 --> 01:10.863
If he needs anything,
get it to him.

01:10.988 --> 01:12.740
You were right about
the women's league.

01:12.907 --> 01:15.493
We'll make Gully put you in
a match with one of his women.

01:15.659 --> 01:16.827
You get in that ring
at Dystopia

01:16.994 --> 01:18.078
and just say,
"Shove it up your ass.

01:18.245 --> 01:19.663
I'm here to sparkle."

01:19.789 --> 01:20.998
And I'll be there
to protect you.

01:21.165 --> 01:23.501
[Gully]
Hey, listen up, Crystal.

01:23.626 --> 01:27.838
This right here is a two-year
contract for you to join FWD.

01:28.005 --> 01:30.341
You get the hell away from her.

01:30.508 --> 01:32.510
You cannot buy Crystal Tyler.

01:32.676 --> 01:34.553
She's no sellout...

01:34.719 --> 01:36.347
like you!

01:36.514 --> 01:38.307
-[whack]
-[Jack groans]

01:38.432 --> 01:39.558
Nice writing, Jack.

01:41.060 --> 01:43.771
[exciting music]

01:43.938 --> 01:46.690
♪ ♪

01:46.856 --> 01:48.400
Wherever you are, Jack Spade,

01:48.567 --> 01:50.361
this isn't over.

01:50.528 --> 01:53.614
-Dystopia for life!
-[crowd cheers]

01:53.781 --> 01:55.241
[Brooks] Excuse me.

01:55.366 --> 01:56.700
Somebody told me that
you work with Crystal Tyler

01:56.867 --> 01:58.660
-and the Spade brothers.
-I do.

01:58.828 --> 02:00.162
I'm Brooks Rizzo.

02:00.329 --> 02:02.081
I would love to know
more about them.

02:02.248 --> 02:03.958
Like what?

02:04.124 --> 02:05.417
Everything.
[small laugh]

02:06.627 --> 02:09.380
[mellow rock music plays]

02:09.547 --> 02:12.216
♪ ♪

02:12.383 --> 02:17.847
[singer]
♪ I'm not waiting for ♪

02:18.013 --> 02:21.892
♪ The answer ♪

02:22.059 --> 02:23.477
♪ ♪

02:23.644 --> 02:26.396
♪ I will ♪

02:26.564 --> 02:29.024
♪ Walk in the shore ♪

02:29.191 --> 02:31.610
♪ To find you ♪

02:31.777 --> 02:34.905
♪ To find ♪

02:35.072 --> 02:38.075
♪ The peace that's your own ♪

02:38.242 --> 02:40.786
♪ Where you come from ♪

02:40.953 --> 02:44.415
♪ All that you want ♪

02:44.581 --> 02:46.250
♪ ♪

02:46.375 --> 02:49.044
♪ One that's your own ♪

02:49.211 --> 02:51.714
♪ Place to call home ♪

02:51.881 --> 02:54.633
♪ Won't be ♪

02:54.758 --> 02:57.469
♪ Granted ♪

02:57.636 --> 03:01.181
♪ What is fair in love ♪

03:01.348 --> 03:07.104
♪ Is fair in war ♪

03:07.271 --> 03:08.939
♪ ♪

03:09.106 --> 03:12.484
♪ What is fair in love ♪

03:12.651 --> 03:17.281
♪ Is fair in war ♪

03:17.448 --> 03:19.783
♪ One ♪

03:19.950 --> 03:22.578
♪ To one ♪

03:22.745 --> 03:25.456
♪ What's love ♪

03:25.623 --> 03:31.462
♪ In war? ♪

03:31.629 --> 03:34.465
♪ ♪

03:37.468 --> 03:40.804
[mellow music plays]

03:40.971 --> 03:43.015
[Dick Valentino] Number three
on the Dick Valentino

03:43.182 --> 03:46.727
"Top Ten Swerves of the Week"
is not out of WWE,

03:46.852 --> 03:48.812
Ring of Honor, or New Japan,

03:48.979 --> 03:51.774
but Florida Wrestling
Dystopia.

03:51.941 --> 03:53.609
In the build-up to
what's shaping up to be

03:53.776 --> 03:56.946
a hot cross-promotion,
"God of Chaos" Charlie Gully

03:57.071 --> 03:59.198
has stolen DWL's Crystal Tyler

03:59.365 --> 04:00.991
-away from Jack Spade...
-[mimics crowd roaring]

04:01.158 --> 04:02.993
[Dick] and signed her
to a new contract.

04:03.118 --> 04:04.828
Visit Dystopia's Instagram

04:04.995 --> 04:06.663
to see clips of this one,
folks.

04:06.829 --> 04:09.375
-This gal's a star!
-[mimics crowd roaring]

04:09.541 --> 04:10.918
[Dick]
The Duffy Wrestling League

04:11.085 --> 04:12.711
out of Southwestern Georgia

04:12.878 --> 04:14.672
has had a notable run
recently,

04:14.838 --> 04:16.423
with the defection
of Rooster Robbins,

04:16.590 --> 04:18.258
the injury to Bobby Pin,

04:18.425 --> 04:20.386
and the addition
of Rabid Ricky Rabies

04:20.511 --> 04:23.430
and Hall of Famer Wild Bill
Hancock to their roster.

04:23.555 --> 04:25.182
Absent in all of this

04:25.349 --> 04:27.726
has been the Luchador
Diego Cottonmouth.

04:27.893 --> 04:30.020
Maybe Jack Spade
just is not a fan

04:30.187 --> 04:32.773
-of Diego Cottonmouth anymore.
-[Diego sighs]

04:32.940 --> 04:35.067
But the big story
is The Condamned,

04:35.192 --> 04:37.569
the DWL's new
hooded hell-raiser

04:37.736 --> 04:39.113
on a vengeance tour.

04:39.279 --> 04:41.240
Watch out for this guy, folks.

04:41.365 --> 04:43.867
Your friend Dick Valentino
will invite The Condamned

04:44.034 --> 04:46.203
to discuss the drama
at work and play

04:46.370 --> 04:48.455
in the hallowed halls
of the DWL.

04:48.622 --> 04:51.500
If you're making a mess,
make sure you clean it up.

04:51.667 --> 04:53.085
I'm making a vision board.

04:53.210 --> 04:54.837
It's a tool to help me

04:55.004 --> 04:56.547
manifest my goals
for my new gimmick,

04:56.714 --> 04:58.090
"The Condamned," in the ring

04:58.257 --> 05:00.551
but also my own
personal goals in life.

05:00.718 --> 05:02.886
You seem to distractedly
be doing

05:03.053 --> 05:05.222
a lot of very
uncharacteristic stuff.

05:05.389 --> 05:07.433
Not distractedly.
Intentionally.

05:07.558 --> 05:09.893
Mama, I'm realizing that...

05:10.060 --> 05:13.063
I always looked at my mistakes
as like...

05:13.230 --> 05:16.066
malfunctions
instead of what they are--

05:16.191 --> 05:20.279
choices, made by a dude
who's led an unexamined life.

05:20.404 --> 05:22.865
Unexamined because
I've always been preoccupied,

05:22.990 --> 05:25.034
playing four sports a year,

05:25.200 --> 05:27.619
always in the car
going to practice,

05:27.786 --> 05:30.164
at practice, from practice,
from a game,

05:30.289 --> 05:33.959
working out, recovering,
resting,

05:34.126 --> 05:36.420
always trying to improve
so I can compete,

05:36.587 --> 05:38.380
leaving no room for just...

05:38.547 --> 05:40.382
thinkin',

05:40.548 --> 05:41.925
contemplating, reflecting.

05:42.092 --> 05:45.012
How can I be a part
of a greater good?

05:45.179 --> 05:48.432
How can I be a light and help.

05:48.557 --> 05:51.769
And if we don't do that,
then we're just...

05:51.935 --> 05:53.937
wingin' it.

05:54.104 --> 05:55.647
I don't wanna wing it anymore.

05:55.773 --> 05:57.357
That's all fine.

05:57.524 --> 05:59.693
But you appear to be

05:59.860 --> 06:02.988
wildly swingin' from branch
to branch like a monkey.

06:03.155 --> 06:04.448
Leaving Duffy,
returning to Duffy.

06:04.615 --> 06:06.408
Hatin' wrestling,
rediscovering it.

06:06.575 --> 06:08.952
Merging a gimmick
with real life,

06:09.119 --> 06:11.622
callin' that
the result of reflection.

06:11.789 --> 06:15.626
So while you are transforming
"winging it" into your vision

06:15.793 --> 06:18.378
for who you should be,
consider the following:

06:18.545 --> 06:20.798
earnin' a living.

06:22.633 --> 06:24.968
Now, unless you're certain that
that glue

06:25.135 --> 06:27.930
isn't gonna wind up all over
my dining room table,

06:28.055 --> 06:29.848
you lay some newspaper down.

06:38.023 --> 06:41.318
[mellow instrumentals]

06:41.485 --> 06:44.279
[train crossing bell dinging]

06:44.404 --> 06:47.241
♪ ♪

06:56.834 --> 06:59.211
Need us for background, Chief?

06:59.378 --> 07:00.963
Uh, no, I'm good.

07:03.257 --> 07:05.050
-Wait.
-Don't lecture me.

07:05.217 --> 07:07.302
-One word is not a lecture.
-It is from you.

07:07.469 --> 07:08.846
Please wait
till we get good news.

07:09.012 --> 07:10.347
We may not get good news.

07:10.514 --> 07:12.224
Then save it
until we get bad news

07:12.391 --> 07:15.352
so there's more for us to drown
our sorrows with together.

07:19.189 --> 07:20.774
[country western music
in background]

07:20.941 --> 07:22.985
[young Willie] I gotta say,
Bill, it's all so excitin'!

07:23.152 --> 07:25.070
Amen!
We are on the verge, Willie.

07:25.237 --> 07:27.072
[Willie laughs]

07:27.239 --> 07:29.366
What do y'all think
Ted Turner's really like?

07:29.533 --> 07:31.201
Ted Turner's
just a good ole boy.

07:31.326 --> 07:34.037
Stop movin' 'less you wanna
get real stuck like a pig.

07:34.163 --> 07:35.414
I can't believe Ted Turner's

07:35.581 --> 07:37.541
even talkin' about us
wrestling on TV!

07:37.708 --> 07:39.751
Because his man Eric Bischoff's
seen what we do.

07:39.918 --> 07:42.504
'Cause word's out about
how we do what we do.

07:42.629 --> 07:45.883
Now Ted's about to pay us
to do more of what we do.

07:46.048 --> 07:47.843
W-C-W!

07:47.968 --> 07:49.761
[both chanting] W-C-W!

07:49.887 --> 07:51.138
[all] W-C-W!

07:54.725 --> 07:57.519
I'm gonna go ahead and stash
the liquor in the bathroom.

07:57.644 --> 08:00.314
People get judge-y about
booze at work nowadays.

08:00.480 --> 08:02.316
-Good idea.
-I have them on occasion.

08:02.482 --> 08:04.318
[Willie] Hey.
Just be yourself.

08:04.484 --> 08:05.777
Seems to be workin' for me.

08:05.903 --> 08:07.279
I was talking to Jack.

08:07.404 --> 08:09.031
[Ace sighs]

08:12.868 --> 08:15.746
Ace, look at you,
all geared up.

08:15.913 --> 08:17.915
Very method.

08:18.081 --> 08:19.750
It's what he came
to see, ain't it?

08:21.376 --> 08:22.336
Damn it!

08:22.501 --> 08:24.004
[Willie] What?
What's wrong?

08:24.171 --> 08:25.672
I forgot the crown.
Should I go home and get it?

08:25.839 --> 08:27.841
-[Jack] I think we're good.
-[car door closes]

08:28.008 --> 08:29.592
Okay. He's here.

08:29.760 --> 08:31.553
-[Debbie] Brooks? Hi.
-[Jack] All right.

08:31.720 --> 08:32.971
Deb's gonna bring him up.

08:33.096 --> 08:35.265
Well, good luck to
the both of you then.

08:35.390 --> 08:38.018
Every question he asks,
ask three of him.

08:38.185 --> 08:39.811
People love
talking about themselves.

08:39.978 --> 08:41.813
So, ferme la bouche.

08:41.939 --> 08:43.774
-Always a good strategy.
-Yeah.

08:43.899 --> 08:46.151
-Ferme la bouche, la douche.
-[Wild Bill chuckles]

08:46.318 --> 08:49.196
[Willie] Okay. Well, you
text us if you need rescuing.

08:49.363 --> 08:51.698
-[Ace] Oh, we got this.
-All right, good, good luck.

08:51.823 --> 08:54.284
That's pretty wet--you're
gonna wanna wipe that off.

09:02.209 --> 09:03.627
You think
he's gonna be all right?

09:03.752 --> 09:05.629
-Time will tell.
-Maybe we should go back in.

09:05.796 --> 09:07.256
-We weren't invited.
-Exactly my point.

09:07.381 --> 09:09.341
-Here we go again.
-[sighs]

09:09.466 --> 09:11.802
Stay present and preoccupied.

09:11.969 --> 09:13.553
Focus elsewhere
for more productive ends.

09:13.720 --> 09:15.013
Let's rustle up the troops.

09:15.180 --> 09:16.765
If we're gonna take this
promotion to the next level,

09:16.932 --> 09:18.350
we gotta get a whole
lot better at this one,

09:18.475 --> 09:19.977
tout suite!

09:20.143 --> 09:21.979
-Staci Spade, lookin' sharp.
-[Staci] Morning, Bill.

09:22.145 --> 09:23.563
-Morning, Willie.
-Morning.

09:23.730 --> 09:25.691
-Did the meeting start?
-Just about to, I believe.

09:25.857 --> 09:26.984
Do I have any food in my teeth?

09:27.150 --> 09:28.235
My eyes are terrible.

09:28.402 --> 09:29.736
-You're good.
-Thanks.

09:29.903 --> 09:31.697
Fingers crossed.

09:32.739 --> 09:34.366
I don't get it.
Jack doesn't invite us,

09:34.533 --> 09:37.327
the two people who made this
possible, and he invites her?

09:37.494 --> 09:38.912
Why?

09:39.037 --> 09:40.789
First of all,
because she's his wife.

09:40.956 --> 09:42.165
Second, same reason
I'd invite her

09:42.332 --> 09:44.001
if I was having that meeting.

09:44.167 --> 09:46.169
A smart woman makes any man
look smarter and stable.

09:46.336 --> 09:48.880
Just like you do for me,
ravishing princess.

09:49.047 --> 09:50.507
I gotta get in the Dome.

09:50.674 --> 09:52.426
My master class
is about to begin.

09:57.222 --> 09:58.849
[newscaster] Yesterday,
in a surprise verdict,

09:59.016 --> 10:01.101
former football star
OJ Simpson

10:01.268 --> 10:03.478
was found not guilty of murder

10:03.645 --> 10:07.190
in the case of Nicole Brown
Simpson and Ron Goldman.

10:07.357 --> 10:09.693
With more on the story,
we're going to Tim Felix.

10:09.860 --> 10:11.528
[Tim] That's right,
I'm here now...

10:11.695 --> 10:12.904
Howdy.

10:13.071 --> 10:14.948
Tom Spade to see Mr. Turner.

10:15.115 --> 10:16.700
Yes, Mr. Spade, welcome.

10:16.867 --> 10:18.577
I'll let Mr. Turner
know you're here.

10:21.371 --> 10:23.874
[Joe] There he is.
Looking sharp, Tom.

10:24.041 --> 10:25.751
Joe, I can't thank you
and Eric enough

10:25.917 --> 10:27.753
for your belief in me
in this introduction.

10:27.919 --> 10:29.713
You're a heck of a wrestler,
Tom--easy to do.

10:29.880 --> 10:32.382
-Morning, Delores.
-Morning, Mr. Canniff.

10:32.549 --> 10:34.676
Your boy OJ
had a lucky day, eh?

10:34.843 --> 10:37.429
Oh, he's not my boy,
Mr. Canniff.

10:38.430 --> 10:39.806
Ted is gonna love you.

10:39.931 --> 10:41.683
Ted is just very invested
in the talent

10:41.808 --> 10:43.560
that represents his name
and his networks.

10:43.727 --> 10:45.395
Don't BS him.

10:45.562 --> 10:47.064
He's sincere. Real.
Confident.

10:47.230 --> 10:48.732
And that's why he's gonna like
you.

10:48.899 --> 10:50.734
Just be yourself.

10:50.901 --> 10:52.819
I'm off to Houston.
I'll call you tonight.

10:54.529 --> 10:55.739
[phone rings]

10:57.908 --> 10:59.785
[Delores] Ted Turner's office.
Can I help you?

11:01.536 --> 11:02.746
Hi.

11:10.670 --> 11:13.673
Meeting's still going.
That's a good sign.

11:13.840 --> 11:15.467
[Wild Bill] One would think.

11:17.552 --> 11:20.889
So how long till
we're on WCW Nitro?

11:21.056 --> 11:23.642
Not in our control.
In due time.

11:23.809 --> 11:26.103
How do I let 'em know I don't
wanna just be your valet?

11:26.228 --> 11:28.271
By being the best
valet you can be.

11:28.397 --> 11:30.524
Boo. Bad answer.

11:30.690 --> 11:32.734
We just gotta make each
spot in our matches shine.

11:32.859 --> 11:34.820
Word will get around
that you wanna wrestle.

11:34.945 --> 11:37.447
We just gotta work hard
and do whatever they ask

11:37.614 --> 11:39.282
before we ask for what we want.

11:39.449 --> 11:40.784
But we still got to speak up.

11:40.951 --> 11:42.953
We speak up by making
ourselves indispensable.

11:43.120 --> 11:44.788
With no drama.

11:44.955 --> 11:46.623
That's no way to
get ahead fast.

11:46.790 --> 11:48.250
You watch how soon
we climb the ladder

11:48.375 --> 11:49.876
not by asking for anything

11:50.001 --> 11:51.920
but by being hard-workin'
and reliable.

11:53.338 --> 11:54.506
[Willie laughs]

11:58.927 --> 12:00.512
Mr. Turner begs your pardon,

12:00.637 --> 12:02.472
but he'll be just
a few more minutes.

12:07.936 --> 12:09.813
[Willie] What the hell could
they still be talking about?

12:09.938 --> 12:11.189
Yachts.

12:11.356 --> 12:12.816
I'm gonna get some more smokes.

12:12.941 --> 12:15.819
Uh...you got any dough?
I'm skint.

12:18.905 --> 12:20.365
I'll get some snacks too.

12:20.490 --> 12:22.159
More than beef jerky this time!

12:22.325 --> 12:23.618
[Wild Bill] Will do, milady.

12:23.743 --> 12:25.954
Even pay you back with
interest, once we make it.

12:26.830 --> 12:28.415
[laughs] Splurge.

12:28.582 --> 12:31.001
More time Tom's schmoozing Ted,
more rich we're gonna be.

12:32.502 --> 12:34.004
Don't bank that cash yet.

12:34.171 --> 12:35.839
Money changes people.

12:36.006 --> 12:37.924
Especially
'fore the money comes.

12:38.091 --> 12:40.051
For all we know, Tom's up there
cutting us out.

12:40.218 --> 12:42.137
He would never do that.

12:42.262 --> 12:45.140
Judas betrayed the Son of
God for 30 pieces of silver.

12:45.265 --> 12:47.476
Ted Turner's got
a Fort Knox of silver.

12:47.642 --> 12:49.144
[Willie laughs]

12:54.191 --> 12:55.817
[door opens]

12:57.861 --> 12:59.529
I beg your pardon, Mr. Spade,

12:59.696 --> 13:01.448
but Mr. Turner
needs to reschedule.

13:01.615 --> 13:02.949
How come?

13:03.116 --> 13:05.118
I'm not always aware of
the reasons, Mr. Spade.

13:05.285 --> 13:07.871
But I'll reach out this week
to find something convenient.

13:08.038 --> 13:09.372
Well, today was convenient.

13:09.539 --> 13:11.875
I have my own obligations
I put aside.

13:12.042 --> 13:14.044
-I understand.
-Not sure you do.

13:14.211 --> 13:15.712
I'd like to just pop in
and say hello.

13:15.879 --> 13:17.881
He's not there, Mr. Spade.

13:18.006 --> 13:19.424
Now you're just
messin' with me.

13:19.591 --> 13:21.301
I been sittin' here
this whole time, eyes open.

13:21.426 --> 13:22.511
I did not see him leave.

13:22.677 --> 13:24.346
He has a separate entrance.

13:24.471 --> 13:26.723
Now, I'll reach out
later this week,

13:26.890 --> 13:28.683
when I know
the rest of his schedule.

13:28.850 --> 13:31.895
Please do.
I have a schedule too.

13:35.398 --> 13:36.858
[knock on door]

13:37.025 --> 13:39.819
Jack, uh, Mr. Rizzo
has arrived.

13:39.986 --> 13:41.905
[Jack] Thank you, Debbie.
Brooks, welcome.

13:42.030 --> 13:44.115
Jack, good to see you again.

13:44.241 --> 13:47.327
It was a bit of a chaotic
introduction backstage

13:47.452 --> 13:48.912
down there at Dystopia.

13:49.079 --> 13:50.956
We have to keep our heads
down and the kayfabe up.

13:51.122 --> 13:52.666
That's my brother Ace.

13:52.832 --> 13:55.752
Wow. That was really
something last night.

13:55.877 --> 13:57.671
-Pleasure to meet you, Ace.
-[Ace] Thank you so much.

13:57.837 --> 13:59.589
Sorry I couldn't
stay at the show.

13:59.756 --> 14:01.633
I had to duck out
and hide in Jack's car.

14:01.800 --> 14:03.468
It's all good.
I get it.

14:03.635 --> 14:05.637
We appreciate you comin'
to see us here in person.

14:05.804 --> 14:06.846
We know Duffy's out the way.

14:07.013 --> 14:08.348
[Ace] Of everything.

14:08.515 --> 14:10.767
I like the drive here,
all the winding roads,

14:10.934 --> 14:13.270
and then, uh, pulling up on
the water tower, the neon sign.

14:13.436 --> 14:14.854
You got a lotta character
in this town.

14:15.021 --> 14:16.064
We grew up here.

14:16.231 --> 14:18.400
-Our dad...
-God rest his soul.

14:18.567 --> 14:20.110
bought this place
three decades ago.

14:20.277 --> 14:22.487
[Ace] He died last year.

14:22.612 --> 14:24.780
He saw potential.
May I get you some coffee?

14:24.948 --> 14:26.199
Sure. Thank you.

14:26.366 --> 14:28.159
Hey. Sorry, I'm late.

14:29.202 --> 14:31.121
Brooks, this is
the lovely Staci Spade,

14:31.288 --> 14:32.872
who thankfully
spilled a beer on me

14:32.998 --> 14:35.041
at a Georgia/Florida football
tailgate 10 1/2 years ago.

14:35.166 --> 14:37.002
[Staci]
Yeah. Being clumsy paid off.

14:37.168 --> 14:39.504
I got this handsome piece of
meat called Jack out of it.

14:39.629 --> 14:40.839
Pleased to meet you.

14:40.964 --> 14:43.133
-Mrs. Spade.
-No, please, call me Staci.

14:43.258 --> 14:44.301
W-we're so appreciative
you're taking time

14:44.467 --> 14:45.468
to get to know more about us.

14:45.635 --> 14:47.804
There you are.
Maybe sit.

14:47.971 --> 14:50.348
-Got you right here.
-Oh, yeah.

14:50.515 --> 14:52.142
Uh, as I was telling Jack
on the phone,

14:52.267 --> 14:53.810
our streaming
platform Continuum

14:53.977 --> 14:55.979
is looking to add
a sporting element

14:56.146 --> 14:57.772
to our programming portfolio.

14:57.939 --> 15:00.567
-I wish I knew what that meant.
-[laughter]

15:00.734 --> 15:03.653
It means that we're
a fledgling streaming service

15:03.820 --> 15:05.447
that just got
a big round of funding.

15:05.614 --> 15:06.990
So now we're being
considered for a merger

15:07.157 --> 15:08.658
with an even-bigger
streaming service,

15:08.825 --> 15:10.827
if we can exponentially
grow our subscriber base.

15:10.994 --> 15:12.871
And professional wrestling,
I'm learning,

15:12.996 --> 15:14.164
is very big business.

15:14.289 --> 15:15.665
Very.

15:15.790 --> 15:17.917
We wanna build something
from the ground up.

15:21.171 --> 15:24.174
So maybe you can all
tell me what you're about.

15:24.341 --> 15:26.009
Let's start at the beginning.

15:26.176 --> 15:27.385
The first time
I went off the top rope

15:27.552 --> 15:29.679
-was the day I turned two.
-[laughter]

15:29.846 --> 15:31.598
[Wild Bill] All righty!

15:31.765 --> 15:34.684
I'm instituting a lecture
series here at the DWL.

15:34.851 --> 15:37.020
So open your minds,
shut your mouths,

15:37.145 --> 15:39.314
and take your fuckin' seats.

15:39.439 --> 15:41.191
-[laughter]
-[Debbie] Wow.

15:43.860 --> 15:46.029
The elephant in the room
is not an elephant.

15:46.196 --> 15:48.365
On these very premises,

15:48.530 --> 15:50.408
there is a man
from an entertainment entity

15:50.533 --> 15:52.786
interested in the DWL.

15:52.952 --> 15:56.039
When he leaves, we will learn
how piqued his interest is

15:56.206 --> 15:58.958
and what it might mean
for our future.

15:59.084 --> 16:00.919
Part of what it means

16:01.044 --> 16:04.005
is validation for what
we've accomplished.

16:04.172 --> 16:06.049
We have drawn attention
to Duffy.

16:06.216 --> 16:07.217
-Whoo!
-Whoo!

16:07.384 --> 16:09.636
-[Debbie] All right!
-[Diego] Yeah.

16:09.803 --> 16:11.054
But that's done.

16:11.179 --> 16:13.264
It's in the past.

16:13.431 --> 16:16.685
Right now, every one of us
needs to be thinking,

16:16.851 --> 16:20.772
"What can I do to make our
visitor's interest pay off?"

16:22.816 --> 16:24.192
We all have one thing
in common.

16:24.359 --> 16:26.569
One day we showed up here
with a version of...

16:26.736 --> 16:28.905
-knock-knock. I wanna wrestle.
-[light laughter]

16:29.030 --> 16:32.283
Each of us surmised
we had something

16:32.409 --> 16:34.828
other people might marvel at.

16:34.994 --> 16:37.747
Which is a little presumptuous.
And a little insane.

16:37.914 --> 16:40.375
Truth is,
no one needs what we do.

16:40.542 --> 16:44.254
We are the very definition of
a nonessential industry,

16:44.421 --> 16:46.631
one we've invited ourselves
into.

16:46.798 --> 16:48.466
You gotta ask yourself,

16:48.633 --> 16:51.803
"Do I have what it takes?"

16:51.970 --> 16:55.515
Some might say,
"Yes, Bill. I worked hard.

16:55.682 --> 16:57.934
I paid my dues."

16:58.101 --> 16:59.352
Don't.

16:59.519 --> 17:02.480
Entitlement is a sin.

17:03.772 --> 17:07.944
"Hard work pays off" is one
of the biggest lies in life.

17:08.111 --> 17:10.697
Hard work is just hard work.
Will it pay off?

17:10.864 --> 17:12.949
Shit, flip a coin.

17:13.116 --> 17:14.617
This business
is littered with folks

17:14.784 --> 17:17.620
who worked their ass off,
got jack shit to show for it.

17:19.456 --> 17:23.543
We better be askin'
"How can we be exceptional?"

17:23.710 --> 17:27.338
I am lookin' for keepers
of the flame here, folks.

17:27.464 --> 17:29.340
Come up with something great.

17:29.507 --> 17:30.675
Go back through history.

17:30.842 --> 17:33.219
Elizabethan drama,
commedia dell'arte--

17:33.386 --> 17:36.639
the average storytelling mode
lasts a generation

17:36.765 --> 17:39.058
before it becomes too familiar,
too trite.

17:39.225 --> 17:41.644
The vessel no longer
serves as a conduit

17:41.770 --> 17:44.397
for a vital
and heartbreaking narrative

17:44.522 --> 17:47.192
on which the human soul
thrives.

17:47.358 --> 17:49.861
It becomes dismissible.

17:50.028 --> 17:53.865
That is where
we are with wrestling...

17:53.990 --> 17:56.242
at the tail fucking end.

17:56.409 --> 17:59.579
About to become dismissible,
a useless vessel.

17:59.746 --> 18:01.039
Let me state again:

18:01.206 --> 18:03.374
no one is asking us
to wrestle.

18:03.541 --> 18:07.504
Our risk of life and limb
is our choice.

18:07.670 --> 18:13.051
So what promise will we make to
ourselves to make it worth it?

18:13.176 --> 18:14.761
[soft, stirring music]

18:14.886 --> 18:16.846
Pick up a pen and a notebook
and start writing down

18:17.013 --> 18:18.389
what you want
from this endeavor

18:18.515 --> 18:20.809
and what you are
willing to do to get it.

18:20.934 --> 18:26.606
Only then can we start
working on our goals together.

18:26.773 --> 18:28.650
Freedom!

18:28.817 --> 18:31.277
-[all whooping]
-Freedom!

18:33.029 --> 18:35.448
[Gully] All right, Rooster.
Make this one count.

18:35.615 --> 18:37.408
-Action.
-[Rooster] All I keep

18:37.534 --> 18:39.869
hearing about is The Condamned.

18:41.913 --> 18:46.417
See, as long as I got
this belt...

18:46.584 --> 18:48.711
the only name that should be
coming out your mouth

18:48.878 --> 18:50.547
is Rooster Robbins!

18:53.508 --> 18:56.427
But it's cool.
Ha ha ha. I get it.

18:56.594 --> 18:59.222
The Condamned, he cool.
And it's like he ziplined

18:59.389 --> 19:01.224
right out the pages
of a comic book.

19:01.391 --> 19:05.061
Flying around the arena
like he's Superman.

19:05.186 --> 19:08.231
Ha ha ha ha!
Whooping on a group of ten men.

19:08.398 --> 19:11.651
So I'm callin' out
The Condamned.

19:11.818 --> 19:13.570
I'm callin' out Jack Spade.

19:13.736 --> 19:16.739
I'm callin' out all of
my so-called friends

19:16.906 --> 19:20.577
that didn't have my back
when I was in the DWL.

19:20.743 --> 19:22.537
And when we meet...oh, yeah,

19:22.704 --> 19:26.416
when we meet, I want the hero
that y'all chose over me.

19:26.541 --> 19:28.251
Yeah. I want The Condamned!

19:28.418 --> 19:30.920
I want him in a last man
standing match.

19:31.087 --> 19:33.089
No more magic tricks.

19:33.256 --> 19:34.757
Nowhere to run!
Nowhere to hide!

19:34.883 --> 19:36.801
Just you, me, one on one,

19:36.926 --> 19:39.596
till there's one of us
left standin'!

19:39.762 --> 19:41.264
Oh, yeah.

19:41.431 --> 19:43.099
And if you got the guts
to show up...

19:45.602 --> 19:47.770
I'll put this belt on the line.

19:47.896 --> 19:49.105
Boom!

19:49.272 --> 19:50.481
Fantastic. Okay.

19:50.648 --> 19:51.983
Just do it one more time.

19:52.108 --> 19:53.776
Slow it down a little bit.
You're talkin' too fast.

19:53.943 --> 19:55.278
Look, I ain't slowin'
it down to be corny.

19:55.445 --> 19:56.779
Yeah, I don't know about
corny.

19:56.946 --> 19:57.780
Just slow it the fuck down
every once in a while

19:57.947 --> 19:58.948
so I know what you're saying.

19:59.115 --> 20:00.575
-People know what I mean.
-The people.

20:00.742 --> 20:02.076
I'm the people.
I'm the people,

20:02.243 --> 20:02.952
and I don't know
what you're saying.

20:03.119 --> 20:04.829
And I wrote it.

20:04.996 --> 20:06.539
-[Paul] Hey, Charlie.
-[Gully] Yes, sir.

20:06.664 --> 20:08.833
I got the engagement numbers
from last week's show.

20:09.000 --> 20:11.920
Crystal had the biggest pop we
ever had for a lady wrestler.

20:13.171 --> 20:14.130
Holy shit.

20:14.297 --> 20:15.256
Crystal.

20:16.257 --> 20:17.342
Crystal.

20:18.134 --> 20:20.511
-More Crystal.
-I can read.

20:22.764 --> 20:25.016
[phone tune plays]

20:25.183 --> 20:26.517
The fuck you want?

20:26.684 --> 20:28.102
Well, don't you have
the prettiest mouth?

20:28.269 --> 20:30.104
Fuck you.
Whadda you want?

20:30.271 --> 20:32.482
I want Crystal.
And not in the biblical sense.

20:32.649 --> 20:34.567
In the financially
remunerative sense.

20:34.734 --> 20:36.027
In the
"we both know she's a star

20:36.194 --> 20:37.487
"who's never gonna get her due

20:37.612 --> 20:39.030
"in a world
where Jack and Ace Spade

20:39.197 --> 20:40.823
come first, second, third,
and fourth" sense.

20:40.949 --> 20:42.450
Yeah, well,
I want a '55 Corvette

20:42.617 --> 20:44.077
and a bottle of Macallan 25,

20:44.243 --> 20:46.162
but we all learn to live
with disappointment.

20:46.287 --> 20:47.997
[chuckles] Willie, we've been
dancing around each other

20:48.164 --> 20:49.707
a while now,
and if there's a moment

20:49.874 --> 20:51.501
to jump ship, this is it.

20:51.668 --> 20:54.295
Things are about to become
highly rewarding down here.

20:54.462 --> 20:56.714
This Brooks Rizzo fella
seems to be real sweet on me.

20:56.881 --> 20:58.633
You sure you're the only one
he's sweet on?

20:58.758 --> 20:59.968
Times a-wasting, Willie.

21:00.134 --> 21:02.720
This train is
leaving the station.

21:02.887 --> 21:04.722
You want me jumping off
ships, jumping on trains?

21:04.847 --> 21:07.350
What the fuck's going on?
Sounds like a shitty trip.

21:07.517 --> 21:10.478
[Gully] I want Crystal
to defect to Dystopia.

21:10.603 --> 21:12.897
For real, not for kayfabe.

21:13.022 --> 21:14.649
And I want you to be her
front-of-house manager.

21:14.816 --> 21:16.192
You should've been
front-of-house a long time ago

21:16.359 --> 21:17.902
not skulking in the shadows

21:18.069 --> 21:19.696
like Miss Havisham
in her fuckin' wedding veil.

21:19.862 --> 21:21.406
[Willie]
Maybe I like the shadows.

21:21.572 --> 21:22.824
Yeah, that's like saying
you like anal warts.

21:22.991 --> 21:24.200
You could have been Crystal.

21:24.367 --> 21:25.785
I don't live in the past.

21:25.952 --> 21:27.495
Go talk to Crystal.

21:27.662 --> 21:30.039
Float it out there.
Send it up the flagpole.

21:30.206 --> 21:32.166
See who salutes.

21:32.291 --> 21:33.876
And while you're wondering

21:34.043 --> 21:35.545
who you're gonna pledge
allegiance to,

21:35.670 --> 21:39.215
I want you to just have a think
about what you want, Willie.

21:39.382 --> 21:40.425
For yourself.

21:40.591 --> 21:42.885
For your future.

21:43.052 --> 21:45.138
-Tick-tock, Fucky.
-[beep]

21:45.304 --> 21:48.433
[somber music plays]

21:48.599 --> 21:50.768
Hey, heard you were
heading to Atlanta

21:50.935 --> 21:52.895
for Ted turnaround number two.

21:53.062 --> 21:54.772
Second attempt
at round number one.

21:54.897 --> 21:57.066
I'm glad Ted finally broke
himself free six months later.

21:57.233 --> 21:58.693
You want company
on the ride up?

21:58.860 --> 22:00.361
It's still all so exciting.

22:02.196 --> 22:03.698
Willie, I need to let you
in on something.

22:03.865 --> 22:05.700
Somethin' serious.

22:07.035 --> 22:08.077
Um...

22:08.244 --> 22:09.579
Are you and Carol splitting up?

22:09.746 --> 22:11.247
-No. Why would--
-Sorry.

22:11.414 --> 22:12.623
Forget I said that.

22:12.749 --> 22:14.584
I was just worried about y'all.

22:14.751 --> 22:16.669
I just noticed tension lately.

22:16.836 --> 22:18.421
They just want me
up in Atlanta.

22:18.546 --> 22:19.881
I don't wanna go
to the meetin'.

22:20.048 --> 22:21.299
I don't wanna be riding up
for moral support.

22:21.466 --> 22:24.385
They just want me right now

22:24.510 --> 22:26.220
for the WCW.

22:28.139 --> 22:30.058
They don't want Bill?

22:30.224 --> 22:31.434
No, they don't.

22:31.559 --> 22:33.603
Least not yet.

22:33.770 --> 22:36.439
I hope to get some more insight
after I sign my own contract.

22:36.606 --> 22:38.608
And since they don't
want Bill,

22:38.775 --> 22:40.818
they don't want me
as his valet.

22:42.695 --> 22:44.989
It's a terrible business.

22:45.114 --> 22:46.949
Doesn't have to be.

22:50.244 --> 22:51.621
I'll bring you and Bill
up there

22:51.788 --> 22:53.790
once I knit myself
into the organization.

22:55.541 --> 22:58.127
If you say so, I believe you.

22:59.545 --> 23:01.172
And don't tell Bill.

23:01.339 --> 23:02.924
I want to tell him in person.

23:05.176 --> 23:06.928
I'll tell him when I get back.

23:10.807 --> 23:12.517
Tom.

23:12.642 --> 23:15.478
[heavy, edgy music]

23:15.603 --> 23:18.439
♪ ♪

23:19.816 --> 23:20.900
Hey, Willie.

23:21.067 --> 23:22.652
Is the big meeting over?

23:22.819 --> 23:24.779
[Willie] Not yet.

23:24.904 --> 23:26.572
Well, it's a long meeting.

23:26.739 --> 23:29.200
So that's gotta be good,
right?

23:29.367 --> 23:30.993
Yeah, well, not always.

23:31.160 --> 23:33.079
Um, listen, I...

23:33.246 --> 23:34.664
I just got a phone call.

23:34.831 --> 23:36.833
Kind of a weird one from Gully.

23:36.999 --> 23:41.462
He wants you to make your
kayfabe defection real.

23:41.629 --> 23:44.507
He wants you at Dystopia
permanently.

23:44.674 --> 23:46.300
Well, he's an idiot.

23:46.425 --> 23:48.052
No one's disputing that.

23:51.514 --> 23:54.183
You don't actually think
I should do it, do you?

23:54.350 --> 23:57.019
I think that you and me...

23:58.062 --> 23:59.814
I think we need to stop
letting other people

23:59.939 --> 24:01.566
make our decisions for us.

24:03.693 --> 24:06.779
I think we need to
start seeing things clearly

24:06.946 --> 24:08.364
for what they really are.

24:10.908 --> 24:15.830
He wants to bring me on as
your front-of-house manager.

24:15.955 --> 24:18.332
-You ever done that?
-[laughs] No.

24:18.499 --> 24:20.459
-Do you even want to?
-I've never thought about it.

24:21.752 --> 24:23.421
Well, I bet you'd be good.

24:23.588 --> 24:26.090
He's just saying things
he thinks I want to hear,

24:26.215 --> 24:28.050
his audience is so much bigger,

24:28.217 --> 24:30.219
and Brooks Rizzo's
talking to him too,

24:30.386 --> 24:34.473
and this is my...
chance to...cash in.

24:37.685 --> 24:39.478
Do you think I should do it?

24:39.645 --> 24:41.731
No.

24:41.898 --> 24:43.900
But I think you deserve
to know what's out there.

24:44.066 --> 24:45.776
Your offers.

24:45.943 --> 24:48.654
I mean, look, if Jack lands
a deal with this Continuum guy

24:48.821 --> 24:50.907
and it pays off, great.

24:51.073 --> 24:53.326
Great. We never had
this conversation.

24:53.492 --> 24:55.453
But even if that
doesn't work out,

24:55.578 --> 24:58.581
there's still the
women's division here.

24:58.748 --> 24:59.999
Yeah.

25:00.166 --> 25:01.042
As long as Jack
can put together

25:01.209 --> 25:04.170
the money to get it going.

25:04.337 --> 25:07.173
[somber music]

25:07.340 --> 25:09.842
♪♪♪

25:10.009 --> 25:12.345
There's all the friends
that I've made here,

25:12.511 --> 25:16.182
you know, everything that
we're...building together.

25:16.307 --> 25:18.684
Yeah, well, sometimes

25:18.851 --> 25:22.313
people get so comfortable
with the "building,"

25:22.480 --> 25:24.732
they get scared of
the "getting."

25:26.275 --> 25:28.152
Look, I'm not telling you what
to do,

25:28.277 --> 25:30.029
'cause I don't
even know what I would do.

25:31.739 --> 25:33.532
The good part is
we don't gotta decide

25:33.699 --> 25:35.785
until we see how
it all plays out.

25:35.952 --> 25:37.995
And now you got
some choices.

25:45.836 --> 25:47.505
[Crystal sighs]

25:49.465 --> 25:52.426
[background chatter]

25:53.344 --> 25:55.054
[Joe] Thank you
for being patient, Tom.

25:55.221 --> 25:56.764
Ted's got a lot going on.

25:56.931 --> 25:58.599
But he wouldn't be
meeting with you

25:58.766 --> 26:00.559
if he didn't want to
meet with you.

26:00.685 --> 26:02.728
Go in there and knock him dead.

26:02.895 --> 26:03.771
Thanks, Joe.

26:03.938 --> 26:05.564
Will do.

26:05.690 --> 26:08.567
[suspenseful music plays]

26:08.693 --> 26:11.570
♪ ♪

26:28.796 --> 26:31.215
Mr. Spade, I'm so sorry,

26:31.382 --> 26:33.634
but Mr. Turner
has got to reschedule again.

26:35.177 --> 26:36.679
-[Joe exhales]
-There's a way

26:36.804 --> 26:38.973
you treat people, and this is
not the way you treat people.

26:39.098 --> 26:40.308
This is not the way!

26:40.474 --> 26:42.226
Look, Tom,
please don't do this.

26:42.393 --> 26:43.686
You don't do this Joe!
I'm a man.

26:43.811 --> 26:45.688
You don't treat
a man like this.

26:45.855 --> 26:47.189
I don't care
how much money he has,

26:47.356 --> 26:50.067
how many yachts he's got,
how soft his hands have become.

26:50.234 --> 26:51.527
It appears he doesn't
know what it means

26:51.694 --> 26:54.196
to be a man any more other
than to let other men wait.

